# Pull Request Template

## Description

This PR implements an example of a hydra config system usage with pytorch-lightning. Hydra is a configuration and experimentation management system (https://hydra.cc/) which streamlines the process of hyperparameter specification and management.

Note that this PR introduces an example of usage, I hope to show possible exploration with hydra config system for experimentation. In addition to managing the hyperparameters through configs, it also provides command line overriding, slurm launcher and easy syncing with wandb.

Would definitely like to get more feedback on the PR.

Fix #(issue)

<!-- Please include a summary of the change and which issue is fixed.
Please also include relevant motivation and context.
List any dependencies that are required for this change. -->

## Description
This pull request implements PyTorch lightning implementation for deepchem model.


List any dependencies that are required for this change. -->
PyTorch lightning https://www.pytorchlightning.ai/

## hydra + lightning + deepchem

For a future feature we can also explore the integration of hydra (https://github.com/facebookresearch/hydra) with the lightning + deepchem port. I have not included that functionality here because the power of hydra really shines through when running experiments from the command line and not inside notebooks.

Notes on hydra:
- Hydra has available integration with pytorch lightning (https://github.com/ashleve/lightning-hydra-template) which we can build upon.
- Hydra provides functionality for building ML modules and running ML experiments.
- It has a seamless integration with SLURM through [submitit](https://github.com/facebookincubator/submitit) which makes hyperparameter searches easier.

## DGL dependency

This tutorial also answers a question related to DGL discussed in https://github.com/deepchem/deepchem/issues/2594. In this tutorial we have used a GCN (Graph Convolutional Network) which underneath uses DGL. This example works well so potentially there are no serious conflicts with using pytorch lightning with DGL at least.

## Deepchem architecture

There are some conflicts around the lightning modules and deepchem's pytorch models, specification of learning rate, batch size etc. Currently I have shown a proof of concept in this tutorial which writes some boilerplate wrapper code to make things work. Going forward we should think about what would be a good way to integrate these two APIs.

pr_body: # Pull Request Template ## Description Implements the `DCLightningModule` class for enabling pytorch lightning training. The DCLightningModule inherits from the pytorch-lightning [LightningModule](https://pytorch-lightning.readthedocs.io/en/latest/common/lightning_module.html). This module defines the training, validation and test steps for our model. We can use this module to initialise our model based on the hyperparameters. This module will directly build on top of the TorchModel class from deepchem located in deepchem/models/torch_models/torch_model.py. ## Type of change Please check the option that is related to your PR. - [ ] Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue) - [x] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality) - [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would cause existing functionality to not work as expected) - In this case, we recommend to discuss your modification on GitHub issues before creating the PR - [ ] Documentations (modification for documents) ## Checklist - [x] My code follows [the style guidelines of this project](https://deepchem.readthedocs.io/en/latest/development_guide/coding.html) - [x] Run `yapf -i ` and check no errors (**yapf version must be 0.22.0**) - [x] Run `mypy -p deepchem` and check no errors - [x] Run `flake8 --count` and check no errors - [x] Run `python -m doctest ` and check no errors - [x] I have performed a self-review of my own code - [x] I have commented my code, particularly in hard-to-understand areas - [x] I have made corresponding changes to the documentation - [x] I have added tests that prove my fix is effective or that my feature works - [x] New unit tests pass locally with my changes - [x] I have checked my code and corrected any misspellings

# Pull Request Template

## Description

This module defines how the data is prepared and fed into the model so that the DCLightningModule can use it for training and evaluating the model.  This class will implement all the dataloaders required for training and will interface different datasets and featurizers implemented in deepchem e.g. NumpyDataset, MolGraphConvFeaturizer from deepchem.

# Pull Request Template

## Description

This PR implements an example of a hydra config system usage with pytorch-lightning. Hydra is a configuration and experimentation management system (https://hydra.cc/) which streamlines the process of hyperparameter specification and management.

Note that this PR introduces an example of usage, I hope to show possible exploration with hydra config system for experimentation. In addition to managing the hyperparameters through configs, it also provides command line overriding, slurm launcher and easy syncing with wandb.

Would definitely like to get more feedback on the PR.

Make the loss implementation non-local, if the implementation is local then when launching processes for multiple GPUs code breaks. Python uses pickle in the process of forking processes and the pickle fails with the error `torch multigpu AttributeError: Can't pickle local object`.

Benchmarking numbers on zinc 5 dataset:

- 1 GPU  Original Deepchem 10 epochs: 178s
- 1 GPU  Pytorch lightning 10 epochs: 194s
- 2 GPUs Pytorch lightning 10 epochs: 104s
- 4 GPUs Pytorch lightning 10 epochs: 57s
- 8 GPUs Pytorch lightning 10 epochs: 34s


Questions:
1. Is there a better way to do this, one possibility is with https://docs.python.org/3/reference/expressions.html#lambda, I will have to test this way more to make things work.
2. This would require making changes to how loss is specified in other methods also.
